transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Hi, this is Viagra.

Speaker 2: Yeah, how you doing?

Speaker 1: Can I have the phone number that you use for your account?

Speaker 2: 6 3 1 8 7 2 4 1 2 5.

Speaker 1: Mr. Richard Westcott, yes. Yes, so I see that you’ve been receiving Viagra.

Speaker 2: 20 to 30 and oh, you got a great deal, too. Yeah, let me assist you, sir.

Speaker 1: Yeah, I don't want to get them anymore, not automatically anyway, because I don't use them as fast as I get them, believe me.

Speaker 2: Oh, I have like four vials full of them.

Speaker 1: Okay, I can pause you if you like, tell them to stop the monthly and pause you so that way—

Speaker 2: You don't lose the current price that you are because apparently you're getting 30 pills—

Speaker 1: Which is three times the regular quantity for the price that you're paying if you go on the website.

Speaker 2: Yeah, yeah, I have enough to last me the rest of my life. I'm near 70 years old.

Speaker 1: I don't need that anymore, so I just don't—I want to stop coming. I want to stop paying for them.

Speaker 2: No matter how much they are.

Speaker 1: Okay, okay, no problem. Yeah, I was trying to offer to pause so you could reorder at your own leisure.

Speaker 2: But if you’re sure that those for me like you say, gonna keep me the rest—

Speaker 1: You're never gonna reorder again, so you don't need your prescription anymore.

Speaker 2: I don't. My wife sort of gave that up.

Speaker 1: Okay, oh, she should not.

Speaker 2: Well, I know that, but she's having her own problems, so yeah, okay.

Speaker 1: All right, anyway, so that—I mean, I didn't call for a consultation.

Speaker 2: I'm not gonna get the pills anymore.

Speaker 1: Okay, okay. Yeah, I cancelled everything.

Speaker 2: Okay, all right. You all said.

Speaker 1: Thank you. Bye. Bye.
